('2018-09-25 12:20:01', 'Not the best parador I have stayed in.

Free parking on the square was restricted because of the annual festival that takes place throughout September and parking in the underground garage was expensive despite the discount.

Because of the festival we asked for a quieter room. The room was at the back of the parador away from the square so was fairly quiet, was spacious and had with views over the countryside.

The restaurant and service was a bit pretentious with bigger pewter platters and domed covers that were whisked off to present you with your main meal. Despite being half board we had to turn up as soon as the restaurant opened to get a table every evening. With no booking system in place, people were being turned away and told to come back later. Not a very good system. Instead of having free access to the olive oil like in the other paradors,  you were just given a small dish of oil. The white bread (no choice!) was hard, stale and not easy to eat - you soon ran out of oilve oil to soften it. The food and wine were otherwise very good.

There''s not much to Lerma itself (the town walk in the early evening before dinner allowed us to see the best parts) but it does make a good base for visiting Burgos, Santo Domingo del Silos and other tourist attractions in the area.

